{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506975"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2594"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2594"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.31,0.08,0.07,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2594"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54322"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2594"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2594"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39825"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10710"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54322"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of worsening pain and swelling in his right leg. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 122/min, blood pressure 114/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.1\u00b0C. His right leg shows severe cellulitis extending from his ankle to groin crease, with a 2x2 cm abscess on his calf. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe abscess is drained in theatre and a swab returns with a result of \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E sensitive to flucloxacillin. He is started on intravenous flucloxacillin 2 g four times daily, together with bed rest and leg elevation. Four days later, routine blood investigations reveal a deranged electrolyte.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely abnormal blood result?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypokalaemia","Hyponatraemia","Hypercalcaemia","Hypomagnesaemia","Hypophosphataemia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical scenario tests knowledge of one of the adverse effects of penicillin antibiotics, especially flucloxacillin. \u003Cstrong\u003EHypokalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a common side effect of high-dose flucloxacillin therapy, particularly when doses exceed 6 g/24 hours or when treatment is prolonged. In this case, the patient is receiving 8 g/24 hours. There are numerous case reports with up to 40% of patients experiencing hypokalaemia in the absence of other causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen in various clinical conditions, including severe infections such as cellulitis. Fever can also contribute to increased insensible water loss and potentially exacerbate hyponatraemia. However, hyponatraemia is not typically associated with flucloxacillin use and is less likely to develop as a result of the treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in this scenario. It can present with symptoms such as polyuria, polydipsia, constipation, abdominal pain, and confusion. The patient\u0027s medical history does not mention any conditions or medications (such as thiazide diuretics or Vitamin D supplementation) that would predispose him to hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypomagnesaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is also unlikely in this case. It can occur secondary to gastrointestinal losses from vomiting or diarrhoea, or from medications such as proton pump inhibitors. However, it is not a known side effect of flucloxacillin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypophosphataemia\u003C/strong\u003E would require the patient to be severely metabolically deranged, which is not suggested by the clinical picture. Examples of medications that can cause hypophosphataemia include loop diuretics, intravenous insulin and glucose, and certain antiviral therapies, but not flucloxacillin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn these circumstances, an abnormality of any of the other electrolyte values would be unusual. The key to this question is recognizing the association between high-dose flucloxacillin therapy and hypokalaemia. This highlights the importance of routine electrolyte monitoring in patients receiving high-dose intravenous antibiotics, particularly flucloxacillin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Flucloxacillin use is associated with a high rate of hypokalaemia, especially with high doses (\u003E6g/24 hours) or prolonged treatment.","Routine electrolyte monitoring is important in patients receiving high-dose intravenous flucloxacillin."],"references":["van der Heijden C, Duizer ML, Fleuren HWHA, Veldman BA, Sprong T et al. Intravenous flucloxacillin treatment is associated with a high incidence of hypokalaemia. Br J CLin Pharmacol. 2019;85:2886-2890. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6955408/#:~:text=In%20this%20retrospective%20cohort%2C%20treatment,%25%20in%20ceftriaxone%E2%80%90treated%20patients.","Hoorn EJ, Zietse R. Severe hypokalaemia caused by flucloxacillin. J antimicrob chemother. 2008;61(6):1396-98. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/jac/article/61/6/1396/742086"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39825"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2594"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39825"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-03T21:01:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-03T21:03:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2594"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54322"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relation